    "historico-title": "Laboratory History",
    "historico-content":
      "&emsp;&emsp;Since its creation in 1994, the Laboratory of Applied Meteorology to Regional Weather Systems - MASTER - has sought to contribute to the training of undergraduate and graduate students at IAG-USP in the areas of Operational Meteorology and Numerical Modeling of the Atmosphere. Initially located in the basement of the Main Building of IAG-USP, the laboratory had personal computers and servers from various companies, such as IBM, Silicon Graphics, and Sun. Most of the machines were based on 64-bit technology, something advanced for the time, and used the UNIX operating system, allowing the processing of remote sensing products, such as satellites, and the evaluation of products generated by numerical models from various centers, such as the NCEP from the United States, the ECMWF from the United Kingdom, and the CPTEC-INPE from Brazil. Over the years, due to technological advancement and important partnerships with national and foreign institutions, MASTER also started, within its operational environment, integrations with the mesoscale model “Regional Atmospheric Modeling System” - RAMS.<br><br>&emsp;&emsp;In addition to numerical model products, since its creation, MASTER has performed an extremely important activity: the storage of various routine products used in weather forecasting, such as soundings, satellite images, METAR, SYNOP, and surface stations; being a national reference in providing data or information for various types of users, from educational and research institutions to individuals interested in leisure activities.<br><br>&emsp;&emsp;MASTER innovated, in Brazil and South America, the concept of a laboratory supporting teaching and research in Meteorology. The various graduate students who passed through there and later returned to institutions across the country, used the structure and operation of MASTER as a model to set up similar laboratories in their institutions. Today, MASTER still leads innovative activities of this type of laboratory and is among the best in the world in its genre - support for teaching and research in Meteorology.<br><br>&emsp;&emsp;Currently, always based on the tripod “teaching/research/service provision”, MASTER has supported research activities at IAG in projects funded by FINEP, FAPESP, CNPq, and other national (CPTEC, IPH/UFRGS) and foreign (Harvard University) institutions. The support is provided through the development of new functionalities and numerical experiments in weather and climate forecasting models, with particular emphasis on regional processes and interaction between the surface and the atmosphere and transport/transformation of pollutants. MASTER has also offered internships for undergraduate students who become familiar with common Meteorology software (GrADS, NCL, R, among others).<br><br>&emsp;&emsp;As more recent examples of services provided by MASTER, studies on the impact of intense cyclones in the region of Petrobras oil exploration platforms, analysis of climate forecasts for the Government of the State of Bahia, numerical forecasts of wind and waves for Angra dos Reis (Petrobras) can be mentioned. A technical cooperation with the company SOMAR is also maintained on topics related to numerical weather forecasting products. MASTER also provides services for research projects at IAG/USP (FINEP, FAPESP, CNPq projects). One of the main achievements at MASTER Laboratory was the development of an automated operational system for regional weather forecasting that was transferred to various national institutions (Cearense Meteorology and Water Resources Foundation - FUNCEME, Paraná Meteorological System - SIMEPAR, and federal universities such as UFRJ, FURGS, UFPA, and UFCG). Currently, it also performs operational forecasts of the concentration of some pollutants over the metropolitan region of São Paulo.",

